  "prompt": "If time slows down as you approach the speed of light, then what time scale is light on?",
  "response": "The concept of time slowing down as you approach the speed of light comes from Einstein's theory of special relativity. According to this theory, as an object approaches the speed of light, time dilation occurs, meaning that time slows down relative to an observer who is not moving at that speed. \n\nFor something traveling at the speed of light (like a photon), time does not progress in the way we experience it. In the frame of reference of the photon itself, time is effectively at a standstill. This is because, according to the equations of special relativity, as you reach the speed of light, the time experienced by the moving object (photon) would theoretically become zero. \n\nIn other words, from the perspective of light, it does not experience time in the way objects with mass do. For a photon, the journey from one point to another is instantaneous, regardless of the distance. However, this description is based on theoretical constructs since photons do not have a rest frame in the traditional sense and their behavior is better described by quantum mechanics.",
